TY  - JOUR
T1  - Optimal Taxation and Human Capital Policies over the Life Cycle
AU  - Stantcheva, Stefanie
Y1  - 2017/08/07
PY  - 2017
DA  - 2017/12/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/694291
DO  - 10.1086/694291
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 1931
EP  - 1990
VL  - 125
IS  - 6
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - This paper derives optimal income tax and human capital policies in a life cycle model with risky human capital. The government faces asymmetric information regarding agents? ability, its evolution, and labor supply. When the wage elasticity with respect to ability is increasing in human capital, the optimal subsidy involves less than full deductibility of human capital expenses on the tax base and falls with age. Income-contingent loans or a deferred deductibility scheme can implement the optimum. Numerical results suggest that full deductibility of expenses is close to optimal and that simple linear age-dependent policies perform very well.
AB  - This paper derives optimal income tax and human capital policies in a life cycle model with risky human capital. The government faces asymmetric information regarding agents? ability, its evolution, and labor supply. When the wage elasticity with respect to ability is increasing in human capital, the optimal subsidy involves less than full deductibility of human capital expenses on the tax base and falls with age. Income-contingent loans or a deferred deductibility scheme can implement the optimum. Numerical results suggest that full deductibility of expenses is close to optimal and that simple linear age-dependent policies perform very well.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/694291
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/694291
Y2  - 2024/03/17
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Design of Debt-Clearing Markets: Clearinghouse Mechanisms in Preindustrial Europe
AU  - Börner, Lars
AU  - Hatfield, John William
Y1  - 2017/08/07
PY  - 2017
DA  - 2017/12/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/694288
DO  - 10.1086/694288
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 1991
EP  - 2037
VL  - 125
IS  - 6
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - We examine the evolution of the decentralized clearinghouse mechanisms that were in use throughout Europe from the thirteenth century to the eighteenth century; in particular, we explore the clearing of nontradable or limited-tradable debts such as bills of exchange. We construct a theoretical model of these clearinghouse mechanisms and show that the specific decentralized multilateral clearing algorithms known as rescontre, skontrieren, or virement des parties, used by merchants in this period, were efficient in specific historical contexts. Our analysis contributes to the understanding of these mechanisms during late medieval and early modern fairs and their robustness during the seventeenth and eighteenth centuries.
AB  - We examine the evolution of the decentralized clearinghouse mechanisms that were in use throughout Europe from the thirteenth century to the eighteenth century; in particular, we explore the clearing of nontradable or limited-tradable debts such as bills of exchange. We construct a theoretical model of these clearinghouse mechanisms and show that the specific decentralized multilateral clearing algorithms known as rescontre, skontrieren, or virement des parties, used by merchants in this period, were efficient in specific historical contexts. Our analysis contributes to the understanding of these mechanisms during late medieval and early modern fairs and their robustness during the seventeenth and eighteenth centuries.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/694288
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/694288
Y2  - 2024/03/17
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Uncertainty Shocks and Balance Sheet Recessions
AU  - Di Tella, Sebastian
Y1  - 2017/08/07
PY  - 2017
DA  - 2017/12/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/694290
DO  - 10.1086/694290
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 2038
EP  - 2081
VL  - 125
IS  - 6
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - This paper investigates the origin and propagation of balance sheet recessions. I first show that in standard models driven by TFP shocks, the balance sheet channel disappears when agents can write contracts on the aggregate state of the economy. Optimal contracts sever the link between leverage and aggregate risk sharing, eliminating the concentration of aggregate risk that drives balance sheet recessions. I then show that uncertainty shocks can help explain this concentration of aggregate risk and drive balance sheet recessions, even with contracts on aggregate shocks. The mechanism is quantitatively important, and I explore implications for financial regulation.
AB  - This paper investigates the origin and propagation of balance sheet recessions. I first show that in standard models driven by TFP shocks, the balance sheet channel disappears when agents can write contracts on the aggregate state of the economy. Optimal contracts sever the link between leverage and aggregate risk sharing, eliminating the concentration of aggregate risk that drives balance sheet recessions. I then show that uncertainty shocks can help explain this concentration of aggregate risk and drive balance sheet recessions, even with contracts on aggregate shocks. The mechanism is quantitatively important, and I explore implications for financial regulation.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/694290
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/694290
Y2  - 2024/03/17
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Financial Constraints and Moral Hazard: The Case of Franchising
AU  - Fan, Ying
AU  - Kühn, Kai-Uwe
AU  - Lafontaine, Francine
Y1  - 2017/08/23
PY  - 2017
DA  - 2017/12/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/694566
DO  - 10.1086/694566
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 2082
EP  - 2125
VL  - 125
IS  - 6
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - Financial constraints are considered an important impediment to growth for small businesses. We study theoretically and empirically the relationship between the financial constraints of agents and the organizational decisions and growth of principals, in the context of franchising. We find that a 30 percent decrease in average collateralizable housing wealth in an area is associated with a delay in chains? entry into franchising by 0.33 year on average, or 10 percent of the average waiting time, and a reduction in chain growth and hence a reduction in franchised chain employment of about 9 percent.
AB  - Financial constraints are considered an important impediment to growth for small businesses. We study theoretically and empirically the relationship between the financial constraints of agents and the organizational decisions and growth of principals, in the context of franchising. We find that a 30 percent decrease in average collateralizable housing wealth in an area is associated with a delay in chains? entry into franchising by 0.33 year on average, or 10 percent of the average waiting time, and a reduction in chain growth and hence a reduction in franchised chain employment of about 9 percent.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/694566
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/694566
Y2  - 2024/03/17
ER  - 

