T1  - The Power of Abortion Policy: Reexamining the Effects of Young Women’s Access to Reproductive Control
AU  - Myers, Caitlin Knowles
Y1  - 2017/08/07
PY  - 2017
DA  - 2017/12/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/694293
DO  - 10.1086/694293
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 2178
EP  - 2224
VL  - 125
IS  - 6
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - I provide new evidence on the relative ?powers? of contraception and abortion policy in effecting the dramatic social transformations of the 1960s and 1970s. Trends in sexual behavior suggest that young women?s increased access to the birth control pill fueled the sexual revolution, but neither these trends nor difference-in-difference estimates support the view that this also led to substantial changes in family formation. Rather, the estimates robustly suggest that it was liberalized access to abortion that allowed large numbers of women to delay marriage and motherhood.
AB  - I provide new evidence on the relative ?powers? of contraception and abortion policy in effecting the dramatic social transformations of the 1960s and 1970s. Trends in sexual behavior suggest that young women?s increased access to the birth control pill fueled the sexual revolution, but neither these trends nor difference-in-difference estimates support the view that this also led to substantial changes in family formation. Rather, the estimates robustly suggest that it was liberalized access to abortion that allowed large numbers of women to delay marriage and motherhood.
